Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE PERMISSION MODE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
File mode constants exposed by the cross-platform dispatcher's prefixed API.
Linux MIPS32 (o32 ABI) uses the same `mode_t` encoding as every other Linux
architecture: the low 9 bits are the rwxrwxrwx permission triplet, encoded
octally as 0644 (rw-r--r--) and 0755 (rwxr-xr-x). The values below are the
decimal equivalents of those octal constants, as required by the syscall ABI
which treats the mode argument as a plain integer. Source: Linux kernel
`include/uapi/linux/stat.h` (S_IRUSR=0400, S_IWUSR=0200, S_IRGRP=0040,
S_IWGRP=0020, S_IROTH=0004, S_IWOTH=0002, S_IXUSR=0100, S_IXGRP=0010,
S_IXOTH=0001). 0644 = 0400|0200|0040|0004 = 420 decimal. 0755 =
0400|0200|0100|0040|0010|0004|0001 = 493 decimal. These values are
architecture-neutral on Linux; MIPS32 inherits them unchanged.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each accessor is a nullary Process returning the constant integer value.
The dispatcher's `MODE_0644 from Syscall` lookup resolves to
`mips32_MODE_0644` on MIPS32 targets via the prefix-name pattern landed in
Wave 2 (Decision 1 / M-2). Wave 2a additionally renames every Process in
this file to the `mips32_` prefix and corrects each `SYS_*` value to the
MIPS o32 ABI numbering (4000+ range, per Linux kernel
`arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h`).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
These accessors are constant returns; the compiler is expected to inline
them at every call site, leaving zero call overhead. Do not introduce any
runtime computation here.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a file permission constant carries no security state. Callers
who use the returned value as a `mode` argument to `creat`/`open(O_CREAT)`/
`mkdir`/`chmod` are responsible for ensuring the requested permission
matches the intended access policy. World-readable (0644) is appropriate
for non-sensitive files; group-and-world-executable (0755) is appropriate
for binaries and directories.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mips32_MODE_0644" returns Integer:
    Return 420  Note: 0644 octal = rw-r--r--
End Process

Process called "mips32_MODE_0755" returns Integer:
    Return 493  Note: 0755 octal = rwxr-xr-x
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: MEMORY MAPPING FLAGS (MIPS32-SPECIFIC)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
MIPS32 Linux defines memory mapping flags in `arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/mman.h`,
which deliberately diverges from the asm-generic Linux values used by x86_64,
ARM, and RISC-V. MAP_SHARED (1) and MAP_PRIVATE (2) match every Linux
architecture. MAP_FIXED retains the asm-generic value 0x10 (16 decimal) on
MIPS. MAP_ANONYMOUS, however, is 0x800 (2048 decimal) on MIPS rather than
the asm-generic 0x20 (32 decimal) -- a long-standing MIPS quirk preserved
for kernel ABI compatibility. The MAP_ANONYMOUS proc above (defined earlier
in this file as 2048) already encodes this correctly; MAP_FIXED is backfilled
here to complete the dispatched-name surface required by the cross-platform
syscall dispatcher. Source: Linux kernel `arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/mman.h`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessor returning the constant integer value. The dispatcher
routes `MAP_FIXED from Syscall` to `mips32_MAP_FIXED` on mips32 targets via
the prefix-name pattern landed in Wave 2. Body is non-side-effecting and
trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant return; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Passing MAP_FIXED to `mmap`/`mmap2` instructs the kernel to map at exactly
the requested address, potentially overwriting an existing mapping silently.
Callers MUST ensure the address range is not in use by other mappings the
process relies on (stack, heap, code, loaded libraries); accidental
overwrites of executable mappings constitute a code-injection primitive.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mips32_MAP_FIXED" returns Integer:
    Return 16  Note: Interpret addr exactly (MIPS asm-generic value)
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: FILE SEEK WHENCE CONSTANTS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
The `whence` argument to `lseek(2)` selects how the supplied offset is
interpreted: SEEK_SET (0) measures from the start of the file, SEEK_CUR
(1) measures relative to the current file position, SEEK_END (2) measures
relative to end-of-file. MIPS32 Linux inherits the same values as every
other Linux architecture, defined in `include/uapi/linux/fs.h` and the POSIX
specification. These match the prefixed dispatcher's expectations and
the `mips32_syscall_lseek` wrapper's `whence` parameter. Source: Linux
kernel `include/uapi/linux/fs.h`.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Nullary Process accessors returning the constant integer values. The
dispatcher routes `SEEK_SET from Syscall` to `mips32_SEEK_SET` on mips32
targets via the prefix-name pattern landed in Wave 2. Bodies are
non-side-effecting and trivially inlinable.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Constant returns; compiler-inlined at the call site. No runtime cost.
Avoid wrapping these in additional indirection; the dispatcher already
selects the platform-correct value at the dispatch boundary.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
Returning a seek-whence constant has no security implications on its own.
Callers that pass user-influenced `offset` values into `lseek` with these
whence flags MUST validate the resulting absolute file position against
the file's permitted range; an attacker-controlled negative offset
combined with SEEK_END can yield an unexpected position prior to file
start, which `lseek` will reject with EINVAL on conforming Linux kernels.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mips32_SEEK_SET" returns Integer:
    Return 0  Note: Seek from beginning of file
End Process

Process called "mips32_SEEK_CUR" returns Integer:
    Return 1  Note: Seek from current position
End Process

Process called "mips32_SEEK_END" returns Integer:
    Return 2  Note: Seek from end of file
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: HIGH-LEVEL SYSCALL WRAPPERS (DISPATCHED SURFACE)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
These ten wrappers form the high-level POSIX-style syscall API exposed by
the cross-platform syscall dispatcher. Each wraps the corresponding MIPS32
o32 ABI syscall number (mips32_SYS_READ=4003, mips32_SYS_WRITE=4004,
mips32_SYS_OPEN=4005, mips32_SYS_CLOSE=4006, mips32_SYS_EXIT=4001,
mips32_SYS_BRK=4045, mips32_SYS_MMAP=4090, mips32_SYS_MUNMAP=4091,
mips32_SYS_FSTAT=4108, mips32_SYS_LSEEK=4019) by routing through the
appropriately-arity generic mips32_syscall_N wrapper, which emits the MIPS
`syscall` instruction with $v0 loaded with the syscall number and $a0-$a3
loaded with up to four arguments (additional arguments spilled to the stack
at 16($sp), 20($sp)). Source: Linux kernel
`arch/mips/include/uapi/asm/unistd.h` (o32 table) and MIPS o32 ABI
specification.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation
Each wrapper resolves the syscall number via the corresponding
`mips32_SYS_<NAME>` nullary Process defined earlier in this file, then
dispatches through the arity-matched generic `mips32_syscall_N` wrapper
(defined earlier) which contains the inline-asm `syscall` sequence. This
indirection allows the dispatcher to swap syscall numbers per-platform
without touching the wrapper bodies. Wave 2 renamed these to
`mips32_syscall_<name>` to match the prefix pattern; the cross-platform
dispatcher in `assembly/syscall.runa` routes through this prefix.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints
Each wrapper compiles to a single tail-call to the underlying
`mips32_syscall_N` helper after loading the syscall number constant. The
compiler is expected to inline the constant load and forward the arguments
directly into the syscall instruction with zero extra register shuffling
beyond what the MIPS o32 ABI requires ($a0-$a3 placement).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope
These wrappers expose direct kernel syscalls; the kernel performs full
argument validation on its side (file descriptor bounds, address-space
ownership, capability checks). Callers MUST still treat all pointer
arguments (`buffer`, `filename`, `statbuf`, etc.) as trusted within the
process address space; passing pointers derived from untrusted input
without prior validation is a memory-corruption vector. The `count`
parameter to read/write MUST be no greater than the actual buffer
capacity; over-large counts that exceed the buffer yield kernel-mediated
buffer overflows readable via subsequent leaks.
@End Security_Scope
Process called "mips32_syscall_read" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Read from file descriptor (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_READ=4003)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_READ()
    Return mips32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_write" takes fd as Integer, buffer as Integer, count as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Write to file descriptor (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_WRITE=4004)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_WRITE()
    Return mips32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, buffer, count)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_open" takes filename as Integer, flags as Integer, mode as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Open a file (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_OPEN=4005)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_OPEN()
    Return mips32_syscall_3(syscall_num, filename, flags, mode)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_close" takes fd as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Close a file descriptor (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_CLOSE=4006)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_CLOSE()
    Return mips32_syscall_1(syscall_num, fd)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_exit" takes status as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Exit process immediately (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_EXIT=4001)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_EXIT()
    Return mips32_syscall_1(syscall_num, status)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_brk" takes addr as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Adjust program break (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_BRK=4045)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_BRK()
    Return mips32_syscall_1(syscall_num, addr)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_mmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer, prot as Integer, flags as Integer, fd as Integer, offset as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Map memory region (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_MMAP=4090, 6 args via mips32_syscall_6)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_MMAP()
    Return mips32_syscall_6(syscall_num, addr, length, prot, flags, fd, offset)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_munmap" takes addr as Integer, length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Unmap memory region (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_MUNMAP=4091)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_MUNMAP()
    Return mips32_syscall_2(syscall_num, addr, length)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_fstat" takes fd as Integer, statbuf as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get file status by fd (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_FSTAT=4108)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_FSTAT()
    Return mips32_syscall_2(syscall_num, fd, statbuf)
End Process

Process called "mips32_syscall_lseek" takes fd as Integer, offset as Integer, whence as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Reposition file offset (MIPS32 mips32_SYS_LSEEK=4019)
    Let syscall_num be mips32_SYS_LSEEK()
    Return mips32_syscall_3(syscall_num, fd, offset, whence)
End Process

